Target IP: 10.10.87.62

Reconnaissance


Performing a port scan against the TCP ports returns the result above. There are plenty of TCP ports open. Right away, this machine has ports open for the Active Directory. I will start enumeration with the SMB on ports 139/445 first.


Using the command crackmapexec smb 10.10.87.62, I identified the crucial information above. It looks like the target machine is running the OS Windows 10.0 Build 17763 x64. The domain name is spookysec.local. The TLD .local used by the target machine is not a good practice either.

enum4linux complete on Tue Nov 21 12:37:48 2023

Using the command enum4linux -a 10.10.87.62 returns the result above. There are some crucial information above. The domain name is THM-AD. The scan also found the different default users. Time to enumerate the users further.


I added 10.10.87.62 spookysec.local inside my /etc/hosts file. Now I can perform reconaissance against the target machine via the name spookysec.local from my machine.

Enumeration


This challenge room contains a usernames wordlist for enumeration. Using the tool kerbrute and the provided usernames list, I managed to find sixteen valid usernames as shown above. I used the command ./kerbrute userenum --dc spookysec.local -d spookysec.local userlist to accomplish this. The usernames svc-admin and backup are the most interesting to me from the username enumeration. Time to check which users are ASReproastable.

Exploitation


Using the tool impacket-GetNPUsers, I tried to find the potential users who do not have the Kerberos preauthentication property set. If this setting is not set properly then it is possible to retrieve the password hash of a user from the Kerberos ticket. Using the command impacket-GetNPUsers spookysec.local/svc-admin, I targeted the user svc-admin. I managed to successfully obtain the password hash of this user svc-admin. I tried it against the user backup, but I had no luck. Time to crack the password of the new hash. I saved the new password hash in a file called hash on my machine.


Since the password hash begins with $krb5asrep$23$, I looked at the guide of hashcat to identify the hash id. According to the picture above, the hash id is 18200 and of type Kerberos 5, etype 23, AS-REP.


Using hashcat, I managed to successfully crack the password hash of the user svc-admin as shown above. I obtained the password management2005 of this user. I used the command hashcat hash -m 18200 /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt to crack this password hash.


And bingo! The credentials svc-admin:management2005 works as shown above. I tested it using the command crackmapexec smb spookysec.local -u svc-admin -p management2005. Time to enumerate further as this low privilege host.


Using the command crackmapexec smb spookysec.local -u svc-admin -p management2005 --shares, I identified the interesting shares shown above. There is an interesting share with the name backup as shown above. This user svc-admin has READ acess to this SMB share.

Privilege Escalation


I connected to the backup share using the tool smbclient. The command I used is smbclient \\\\spookysec.local\\backup --user svc-admin, as shown above. There is an interesting file with the name backup_credentials.txt inside this share. This file contains the hash YmFja3VwQHNwb29reXNlYy5sb2NhbDpiYWNrdXAyNTE3ODYw. This looks like a base64 string.


Using the command echo YmFja3VwQHNwb29reXNlYy5sb2NhbDpiYWNrdXAyNTE3ODYw | base64 -d, I obtained the plaintext credentials of backup@spookysec.local:backup2517860 as shown above. Now I have the credentials of the backup user! Is this the backup account for the domain controller? If so, this is an easy win for owning the domain controller.
